Deductive Arguments

	Collection of propositions where one of the propositions(conclusion) follows from the previous proposition(premise)
	
	ex: P1										-
	    P2										|
	    .		Assuming all is true						|
	    .										|
	    .										|	------> Propositional form
	    Pn										|
	    --										|
	    .*.C -> must also be true			# .*. = therefore		|
	   
if true implies true, then the conclusion must be true

	ex: P1:If today is sunny, then today is humid (1st premise)
	    P2:Today is not humid.
	    C: Therefore, today is not sunny. #tentative lol had to go to work
	  				#p1 and p2 = premises. C = conclusion
					
	   Premises: A:Today is sunny.
	   	     B:Today is humid.
		     
		     
		     
Tautology syntax = Within a truth table if there is a false it becomes nullified and therefore doesn't become a tautology. 
			Formula : T -> F = F

Rules of Inference 
1. Addition 
P1: P
C: .*. P v Q				#if you are confused with the symbols, scroll back up into the symbol cheatsheet :)) 

2. Simplification 
	P1: P ^ Q 			P ^ Q 				Q^P 			Q^P
	----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	C: .*. P 			.*. Q 				.*.Q			.*.P]
				
				P^Q -> P
			T t	T	T	T
			T f	F	T	T
			F f	T	T	F
			F f	T	T	F
			
3. Conjunction 
	p1: P					(P1 ^ P2) => C
	P2: Q							\
	ci: p^Q					(P^Q) =>	(P^Q)
						
4. Modus Ponens

	P1: 	P=>Q				[(P=>Q)^P ] = Q
	P2: 	P				
	-------------
	c: .*. Q
	
5. Disjunctive Syllogism
P1: P v Q				[(P v Q) ^ ~P] -> Q
P2: ~P					T   T	T	 
----------				T   T	F	
C: .*. Q				F   T	T	
					F   F	F	
					
